getConnection

public void getConnection(String[] parameters)
Creates a new connection and assigns the first running Worker on the TCP Socket to the connection instance class so that the same socket is used to send messages. For UDP this works the same as createConnection.

Parameters:
parameters - array of String containing the parameters.
parameters[0] argument is always the method name,
parameters[1] argument the name for the connection,
parameters[2] argument is the is the TCP/UDP server port parameters[2] argument is the is the SSL server port port which handles the responses,
If null is used as parameters it sends the allowed parameters list to the XTTProperties.printFail(java.lang.String) method and returns.
See Also:
XTTProperties

startSIPServer

public boolean startSIPServer(String[] parameters)
starts the SIPServer as an instance of SIPServer.

Parameters:
parameters - array of String containing the parameters.
parameters[0] argument is always the method name,
parameters[1] argument is the SIPServer port,
parameters[2] is the SIPServer root directory,
parameters[3] argument is the SIPServer timeout.
If only parameters[0] is submitted the parameters will be taken from the configuration xml document in XTTProperties.
If null is used as parameters it sends the allowed parameters list to the XTTProperties.printFail(java.lang.String) method and returns.
See Also:
SIPServer, XTTProperties

stopSIPServer

public boolean stopSIPServer(String[] parameters)
stops all/one SIPServers and all it's threads.

Parameters:
parameters - array of String containing the parameters.
parameters[0] argument is always the method name, no additional parameters are requeired,
the optional parameters[1] argument is the SIPServer port of the SIPServer to stop, if omitted all running servers are stopped.
If null is used as parameters it sends the allowed parameters list to the XTTProperties.printFail(java.lang.String) method and returns.
See Also:
SIPServer.closeSocket(String), SIPServer.closeSockets()

setServerReturnCode

public void setServerReturnCode(String[] parameters)
Overrides the normal SIP Return code with a custom code.

Parameters:
parameters - array of String containing the parameters.
parameters[0] argument is always the method name,
parameters[1] is an integer representing the sip code (0 or less means no override).
If null is used as parameters it sends the allowed parameters list to the XTTProperties.printFail(java.lang.String) method and returns.

setServerReturnMessage

public void setServerReturnMessage(String[] parameters)
Overrides the normal SIP Return Message with a custom code.

Parameters:
parameters - array of String containing the parameters.
parameters[0] argument is always the method name,
parameters[1] is the Message after the response code including the whitespace between message and response code (for "SIP/2.0 200 Ok" it would be " Ok").
If null is used as parameters it sends the allowed parameters list to the XTTProperties.printFail(java.lang.String) method and returns.

sendFreeRequest

public void sendFreeRequest(String[] parameters)
wait for a specified number of SIP requests on the SIPServer.

Parameters:
parameters - array of String containing the parameters.
parameters[0] argument is always the method name,
parameters[1] argument is the optional connection name.
parameters[2] argument is the remote host to connect to.
parameters[3] argument is the remote port to connect to.
parameters[4] argument is either TCP or UDP.
parameters[5] argument is the complete headers of the request INCLUDING the empty line seperating headers and body (End every line with CRLF).
parameters[6] argument is the optional base64encoded body (don't forget to add content-length headers).
If null is used as parameters it sends the allowed parameters list to the XTTProperties.printFail(java.lang.String) method and returns.
See Also:
SIPConnection.sendRequest(String,String,int,String,String,String)
